{
  "doc_id": "59731",
  "text": "It has been shown previously that genome segregation into physical domains in Drosophila could be unambiguously explained by differences in chromatin compaction of transcriptionally active and inactive regions, determined by epigenetic profile [CITATION_1] . However, principles orchestrating TADs formation in Drosophila could not be directly translated to mammalian TADs, where CTCF is put forward as the main TAD builder [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . A strong enrichment of CTCF sites near domain borders observed in CEF data favors hypothesis that, as in mammals, this factor plays a major role in organization of chicken fibroblast domains.",
